			<section class="comment">
				<p>Having read the book when it first came out, I found this a very useful memory-jogger. </p>
<p>In particularly, #2 &amp; #8 are interesting.. I have look at these in the area of project management where there is a constant seach for and claims of something new (see my paper at <a href="http://eprints.usq.edu.au/22707/3/McKenna_Whitty_2012_PMAC_2012_PV.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://eprints.usq.edu.au/22707/3/McKenna_Whitty_2012_PMAC_2012_PV.pdf</a>). </p>
<p>Certainly the notion that the &#8220;best&#8221; ideas survive is something to be challenged &#8211; rather, I think, it is the most adaptable &#8211; to environmental pressures, fads etc., which last ahead of others which may in fact be mroe fit-for-purpose.</p>
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/ten-myths-of-innnovation/?replytocom=85220#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-85220", "85220", "respond", "12107")'>Reply</a> 			</section>
			
